<div class="page-head"><h2>Host on AWS Lightsail</h2></div>

<DocsPage Slug="hosting">
    <h1>Host SpawnWeaver on AWS Lightsail</h1>
    <p class="lead">
        Put the whole backend — API, database, and automatic HTTPS — on one small Lightsail
        instance in about 15 minutes. After this you'll have a real <code>https://your-domain</code>
        that players and the SDK connect to.
    </p>

    <p>You'll use one <strong>Docker Compose</strong> stack: <strong>Caddy</strong> (handles HTTPS
        and WebSockets for you) → the <strong>API</strong> → <strong>PostgreSQL</strong>. You need a
        domain you can edit DNS for, and an AWS account.</p>

    <h2>1. Create the instance</h2>
    <p>In the Lightsail console, create an instance: platform <strong>Linux/Unix</strong>, blueprint
        <strong>OS Only → Ubuntu 24.04 LTS</strong>, the <strong>$10/mo</strong> plan (2 GB) to start.
        Download the SSH key (<code>.pem</code>) if you don't already have it.</p>

    <h2>2. Give it a static IP &amp; open the firewall</h2>
    <p>Lightsail → <strong>Networking</strong> → <strong>Create static IP</strong> and attach it
        (otherwise the IP changes on reboot). Then on the instance's
        <strong>Networking → IPv4 Firewall</strong>, add rules for <strong>HTTP (80)</strong> and
        <strong>HTTPS (443)</strong>. Without these two, Caddy can never issue a certificate.</p>

    <h2>3. Point your domain at it</h2>
    <p>At your DNS provider, add an <strong>A record</strong> for your domain to the static IP:</p>
    <pre>spawnweaver.example.   A   &lt;your-static-ip&gt;</pre>
    <p>Wait until it resolves (<code>ping spawnweaver.example</code> shows the IP). Caddy needs
        working DNS to issue the HTTPS certificate.</p>

    <h2>4. Install Docker</h2>
    <p>SSH in as the default <code>ubuntu</code> user
        (<code>ssh -i LightsailKey.pem ubuntu@@&lt;your-static-ip&gt;</code>) and install Docker:</p>
    <pre>curl -fsSL https://get.docker.com | sudo sh
sudo usermod -aG docker ubuntu          # run docker without sudo (re-login to apply)</pre>

    <h2>5. Get the code and set your secrets</h2>
    <pre>git clone &lt;your-repo-url&gt; spawnweaver &amp;&amp; cd spawnweaver
cp deploy/.env.example deploy/.env
nano deploy/.env</pre>
    <p>Fill in <code>deploy/.env</code> (it's git-ignored — keep secrets here):</p>
    <ul>
        <li><code>DOMAIN</code> — your domain, e.g. <code>spawnweaver.example</code></li>
        <li><code>ACME_EMAIL</code> — your email (Let's Encrypt expiry notices)</li>
        <li><code>POSTGRES_PASSWORD</code> — any long random string</li>
        <li><code>EMAIL__RESEND__APIKEY</code> — your <a href="https://resend.com">Resend</a> key for sign-up emails
            (leave blank to start — accounts auto-verify until you add it)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>6. Launch it</h2>
    <pre>docker compose --env-file deploy/.env -f deploy/docker-compose.prod.yml up -d --build</pre>
    <p>Caddy fetches an HTTPS certificate within a few seconds. Confirm it's up:</p>
    <pre>curl https://spawnweaver.example/health
# {"status":"ok","service":"Platform.Api","version":"…"}</pre>

    <h2>You're live</h2>
    <p>Now everything points at your domain:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Dashboard &amp; sign-up: <code>https://spawnweaver.example/dashboard</code></li>
        <li>Players connect at: <code>wss://spawnweaver.example/connect</code></li>
        <li>SDK install: <code>iwr https://spawnweaver.example/install.ps1 -UseBasicParsing | iex</code></li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Email for real users</h2>
    <p>The hosted stack requires email verification before sign-in, so add a real sender: create a
        <a href="https://resend.com">Resend</a> API key, <strong>verify your sending domain</strong>,
        set <code>EMAIL__RESEND__APIKEY</code> and <code>EMAIL__FROMADDRESS</code> (e.g.
        <code>noreply@@spawnweaver.example</code>) in <code>deploy/.env</code>, then re-run the compose
        command. Until then, leave the key blank and accounts auto-verify so you can test.</p>

    <h2>Updating &amp; backups</h2>
    <pre># Deploy a new version
git pull
docker compose --env-file deploy/.env -f deploy/docker-compose.prod.yml up -d --build

# Back up the database
docker exec spawnweaver-db pg_dump -U spawnweaver spawnweaver &gt; backup-$(date +%F).sql</pre>
    <p class="muted">For the full reference (operations, restore, troubleshooting) see
        <code>docs/hosting-aws-lightsail.md</code> in the repo (including one-click CI/CD deploys).</p>

